Let $A_0=(0,0)$, $B_0=\left(1,0\right)$, $C_0=\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)$. Divide the trefoil into three congruent regions to produce a parable made out of three such triangles. The region below $CB_0$ is a parabola with focus $s\left(\frac{2}{3},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}\right)$ and directrix
\begin{align*}
y=-\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{align*}
which follows the parabolic equation;
\begin{align*}
\left(x-\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 + \left(y-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}\right)^2 &= \left(y+\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right)\right)^2\\
2x^2-4x+2x\sqrt{3}y-\frac{2}{3}x-\sqrt{3}y &= 0.
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
(y-\sqrt{3}/3)^2 &= -({x-2/3})^2+x-sqrt{7}/6;
\end{align*} <answer>Area of this shape is $\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}$. Therefore, four of them make up the whole trefoil and the answer is $\frac{8}{\sqrt{3}}$. $\blacksquare$</answer>

